    <h1>Hippos: The Gentle Giants</h1>
    <p>Hippopotamuses, or hippos for short, are large, semi-aquatic mammals native to sub-Saharan Africa. They are known for their massive size, their large, incisor teeth, and their aggressive nature.</p>

    <h2>Physical Characteristics</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Weight: Up to 8,000 pounds (3,600 kg)</li>
        <li>Length: Up to 15 feet (4.6 m)</li>
        <li>Height: Up to 5 feet (1.5 m) tall at the shoulder</li>
        <li>Color: Gray to reddish-brown</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Habitat and Behavior</h2>
    <p>Hippos are typically found in rivers, lakes, and swamps. They are social animals and live in groups of up to 40 individuals. Hippos are primarily herbivores and graze on grasses and aquatic plants.</p>

    <h2>Conservation Status</h2>
    <p>Hippos are currently classified as Vulnerable on the IUCN Red List. Their main threats are habitat loss and poaching.</p>

